R><img src=http://www.forthworld.net/fridge/jedi1.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Freshwater Aquarium or Saltwater</span><hr size=1> If you switch and don't want corals the work isn't too bad but it will cost a bit to start.  If you have an undergravel filter now....take it out and throw it away along with your gravel.  Put a good 2-3 inches of araganite or live sand in the bottom.  Go buy a wet/dry filter with bio balls or build a sump for filtration and make sure you have at least 2 power heads in the tank cause you do not want any dead spots in the tank where the water doesn't move.  Even if you are not gonna get corals you should put live rock in the tank cause it helps with filtration and keeping things healthy.  A good cleaning crew of various snails and crabs is a must if you wanna make life easier and keep your tank looking pretty.  I also strongly suggest new lighting.  If you want to make a reef tank and have corals you need a ton of light but even if you don't, having good lighting will help keep your fish healthy.  If you want corals you should get metal halide lights and alot of wattage but for an FO tank you can get VHO or power compact lighting and its not quite so expensive.  You have to have 2 different types of light....Blue lights for morning and evening and white light for the daytime.<br>
<br>
Another thing you may wanna consider is making a refugium.  You can make a refugium instead of a sump or wet/dry filter if you want and they are pretty cool and keep your tank very healthy.  A refugium is more or less just a small tank you put under your main tank and fill it with special mud and certain types of algea.  What it does is when your water cycles through it the bactreia that lives in the mud and the algea eat the bad stuff in your water, cleraning your water and at the same time puts healthy chemicals back into the water before it cycles back to the tank.  It makes your tank much more self sufficient and healthy.  You can find alot of plans on the net for sumps, wet/dry filters, and refugiums and you can make a filtration system that is very good.  <br>
<br>
I would go to the net and do alot of reading and planing before you decide to switch over as it will prolly end up saving you alot of time and money in the long run and give you a tank that is more fun and beatiful than it is work.<br>
<br>
